w the medical and teaching professions helped educate people in their own self-defense and in the process expanded trade unionism, women's consciousness, and civil liberties. He also discusses the antimalarial effort under Mussolini's regime and reveals the shocking details of the German army's intentional release of malaria among Italian civilians-the first and only known example of bioterror in twentieth-century Europe. Comprehensive and enlightening, this history offers important lessons for today's global malaria emergency.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aMalariaxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aMalariaxTreatmentxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aMalariaxTreatmentzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMalariazItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aMosquitoesxControlxHistoryx20th centuryxItaly. 0aMosquitoesxControlzItalyxHistoryy20th century. 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300128437423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300128437.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles